> For others affected that are having trouble figuring out how to use your bitmap fonts with the new pango version from the comments above, here's a guide:

Here is how to mass-convert fonts in this way automatically:

1. Apply the following patch, because fontforge's code to save fonts from scripts is borked:

	```patch
	diff --git a/fontforge/savefont.c b/fontforge/savefont.c
	index dc03246ac..b1cf431c1 100644
	--- a/fontforge/savefont.c
	+++ b/fontforge/savefont.c
	@@ -1113,8 +1113,6 @@ int GenerateScript(SplineFont *sf,char *filename,const char *bitmaptype, int fmf
	    if ( i==ff_otf ) i = ff_otfcid;
	    else if ( i==ff_otfdfont ) i = ff_otfciddfont;
	     }
	-    if ( (i==ff_none || sf->onlybitmaps) && oldbitmapstate==bf_ttf )
	-	oldbitmapstate = bf_sfnt_ms;
	     oldformatstate = i;

	     if ( oldformatstate==ff_none && end[-1]=='.' &&
	@@ -1130,13 +1128,6 @@ int GenerateScript(SplineFont *sf,char *filename,const char *bitmaptype, int fmf
	    else
		strcat(freeme,"ttf");
	    filename = freeme;
	-    } else if ( sf->onlybitmaps && sf->bitmaps!=NULL &&
	-	    (oldformatstate==ff_ttf || oldformatstate==ff_otf) &&
	-	    (oldbitmapstate == bf_none || oldbitmapstate==bf_ttf ||
	-	     oldbitmapstate==bf_sfnt_dfont || oldbitmapstate==bf_otb)) {
	-	if ( oldbitmapstate==ff_ttf )
	-	    oldbitmapstate = bf_ttf;
	-	oldformatstate = ff_none;
	     }

	     if ( oldbitmapstate==bf_sfnt_dfont )
	```

2. Run this script:

	```bash
	#!/bin/bash
	set -eEuo pipefail

	dir=/usr/share/fonts
	mkdir -p out

	find "$dir" -name '*.pcf.gz' | \
		while read -r font
		do
			name=${font##$dir/}
			name=${name//./-}
			name=${name//\//-}
			name=out/$name.otf
			printf 'Open("%s")\nGenerate("%s", "otf")\n' "$font" "$name"
		done | \
			FONTFORGE_LANGUAGE=pe fontforge -script /dev/stdin
	```

Unfortunately, even with the converted fonts, I'm still seeing regressions is Pango-using applications (e.g. icons in i3-bar are misaligned or missing).

I agree with sentiments above that such breaking changes are best done as new major versions, which can be installed side-by-side with old versions to avoid breakage and allow application developers to consider the trade-offs when picking a library major version to use. Generally the discussion above is very disappointing due to how unilaterally the change has been presented, and how there is little evidence of any effort to assess whether the advantages gained by the switch to Harfbuzz was justified the impact caused by the change, but I suppose that's par for the course for GNOME projects.

